Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:03 PM Defendant Denise Lynn Lunsman in court.  Attorney Gabriel Andres Pollak in court for Denise Lynn Lunsman. Attorney James Jay Rennicke Esq in court for State of Wisconsin. Case is on for preliminary hearing.  State calls first witness, Trooper Anthony Olson, who is sworn in by Court and testifies.  Witness has identified the defendant.  Venue is made.  Atty Pollak crosses.  State redirects.  Atty Pollak recrosses.  State rests and asks for bind over.  Court finds probable cause that a crime has been committed and the defendant probably committed it.  The matter is bound over for further proceedings.  The State files information mirroring complaint.
